Have you ever misplaced a photo and you just can't find it? Well, I have, but instead of wallowing in despair, I decided to do something about it.

If you think about it, photos are just a bunch of pixels, and pixels are just a bunch of numbers. If you put enough random numbers together, eventually you'll end up with the photo you've deleted!

Well, almost. It turns out there are quite a few numbers in a picture and if you consider all the possible numbers, you'll realize that it will be quicker to get on a plane and fly to Giza, rebuild the pyramid and take the photo again. Yes, in the universe this was written in the pyramids all got destroyed.

Okay, maybe we can use a smaller camera, you know, like the one your Nokia phone had back in the day. Lets consider a 1 megapixel photo. And lets say each pixel can be expresses as (r,g,b) where r,g and b is a number between 0 and 255. That means that each pixel has 255^3 possible values. That is 16,581,375 total values each pixel can take! Put that to the power of a million, and you have all the possible 1 megapixel images in 8-bit RGB space. Several of them containing the pyramids in Giza.

I gave up on that number. I did however reduce the resolution a bit and tried again to calculate. A 100x100 pixel image gives us 1.6e+72197 possibilities. For your benefit, here is that number as a plain old integer rather than in scientific notation:

Okay, so maybe that isn't going to work so well. How about we just go for a black and white image? Each pixel can be either black or white, 2 options, and there are 10,000 pixels, iow. 2 to the power of 10,000. Wouldn't be that big right? 

<p style="word-break: break-all; font-size: 8pt;">
</p>

Or 1.995e+3011 in scientific notation :) That is still way too many images to generate!

Lets start with a black and white 4x4 pixel imager, only 65,536 options! My laptop can probably do that! Rather than generating thousands of images, let's combine all of them in one big image.

```python
# Generate every image of size 4x4

from PIL import Image
from random import shuffle

s = 4 # side length
rows = 256
cols = 256
image = Image.new('RGB', (cols*s, rows*s) )

universe = list(range(1, 2**(s**2)-1))
shuffle(universe)

for ii, i in enumerate(universe):
    ro = (ii)//cols * s
    co = (ii)%cols * s
    for y in range(s**2):
        color = 255 if i >> y & 1 else 0
        row = y//s
        col = y%s
        image.putpixel( (co + col, ro + row), (color, color, color))

image.save('image-{}.png'.format(universe[0]))
```

And here is the result:

![An image of all possible universes as observed through a 4x4 black and white camera]({{site.baseurl}}/img/2018/image-35357.png)

If you look closely, you'll see the pyramids, somewhere.

The code could use some explaining, or to put it differently, I'm writing this a year after I actually did the little experiment and I would have appreciated if 1 year dumber me actually explained what he did.

First, it's using PIL to create 1 big image. `2**16` is a square, so we can put 256x256 images in a perfect square!

Secondly, what am I doing here?

```python
universe = list(range(1, 2**(s**2)-1))
shuffle(universe)
```

Well, since our images are only black and white, each image can be represented as a 16-bit binary string. So by counting up to `2**16`, we've generated all the possible images. And then we shuffle the numbers, because the sequential pattern doesn't look that good.

Next we generate a picture from the data. We need to determine where in the bigger image each 5x5 images should be put.

```python
for ii, i in enumerate(universe):
    ro = (ii)//cols * s
    co = (ii)%cols * s
```

To convert the number to an image, we look at the value of the bit and break up the consecutive binary string into a 4x4 matrix by putting 255 or 0 at the right row and column.

```python
    for y in range(s**2):
        color = 255 if i >> y & 1 else 0
        row = y//s
        col = y%s
        image.putpixel( (co + col, ro + row), (color, color, color))
```

You could probably do 5x5, that would give you 33.554,432 possible images. If you stick them all together (I leave the geometry for you) it will give you a 838 megapixel image. This will be big, but not impractical, NASA has a [1,545 megapixel image of the Andromeda Galaxy](https://www.spacetelescope.org/images/heic1502a/).

Finally, why the mention of alternate universes? Well, the image we've generated is an accurate depiction off all possible events that occurred, is occurring or will possibly occur in all possible universes as observed by a 4x4 pixel black and white camera!
